{"id":"PRIMARY-1","severity":"HIGH","confidence":"high","file":"server/index.js","line":39,"rule_id":"empty.body.crash","message":"`.update(req.body)` assumes the raw middleware always supplies a Buffer. In-process dispatch of the actual route with no Content-Length/Transfer-Encoding left `req.body` as `{}` and raised `ERR_INVALID_ARG_TYPE` for both a valid empty-body HMAC and an invalid signature, instead of returning 400 and 401 respectively.","criterion_ref":"Signature check runs before body-shape validation: an invalid body with a valid signature is `400`; any body (valid or invalid) with an invalid signature is `401`."}
{"id":"PRIMARY-2","severity":"HIGH","confidence":"high","file":"server/index.js","line":35,"rule_id":"parser.preempts.signature","message":"`express.raw({ type: '*/*' })` applies Express's default 100kb limit before the handler can verify the signature. Actual route dispatch with 102401 bytes and an invalid signature produced `PayloadTooLargeError` status 413, not the required 401, so signature verification is not unconditional for every body.","criterion_ref":"Signature check runs before body-shape validation: an invalid body with a valid signature is `400`; any body (valid or invalid) with an invalid signature is `401`."}
{"id":"PRIMARY-3","severity":"HIGH","confidence":"high","file":"server/index.js","line":35,"rule_id":"raw.bytes.inflated","message":"`express.raw` defaults to `inflate: true`, so `req.body` is decompressed before line 39 computes the HMAC. An actual gzip-encoded request signed over its exact 81 received bytes was inflated to 65 bytes and rejected with 401, demonstrating that the implementation hashes a transformed body rather than the literal received bytes.","criterion_ref":"HMAC must be computed over the exact raw bytes of the request body as received, not a re-serialization of parsed JSON."}
